2500|$|In 1594, John Davis {{published}} an 80-page pamphlet called The Seaman's Secrets which, {{among other things}} describes <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> <b>sailing.</b> [...] It's said that the explorer Sebastian Cabot had used great circle methods in a crossing of the North Atlantic in 1495. [...] Davis also gave the world {{a version of the}} backstaff, the Davis quadrant, which became one of the dominant instruments from the 17th century until the adoption of the sextant in the 19th century.|$|E
50|$|The United States Antarctic Service photographed it on September 28, 1940 {{from the}} air. The Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey {{did the same}} on August 14, 1947 and {{conducted}} a rough survey in December 1958 and November 1960. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named it after the English mathematician Richard Norwood (1590-1675), who promoted <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> <b>sailing.</b>|$|E
