40|$|After thirty years' labouring, {{the author}} {{accomplished}} to exchange the spheric trigonomical equation as follows: log 2 (cos S+ 1) / 2 (cos S+cos Z) =log 2 / 1 +cos H+log 2 (cos S+ 1) / 2 (cos S+cos D) ∫Z 0 sin z/cos S+cos z・dx・log e=∫H 0 sin H/ 1 +cos H・dx・log e+∫D 0 sin D/cos S+cos D・dx・log e It is confidently hoped that this table {{will be used}} to finish the nautical culculations within sufficient accuracy and the least time. Moreover, this new nautical table, conveniently, is well adapted for extending through the astronomical and the geometrical sailings, namely the calulation on the high altitude, the Ex-meridian altitude, the <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> <b>sailing</b> etc., at the same openning of a table...|$|E
50|$|For most {{pairs of}} {{points on the}} surface of a sphere, there is a unique <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> through the two points. The {{exception}} is a pair of antipodal points, for which there are infinitely many <b>great</b> <b>circles.</b> The minor arc of a <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> between two points is the shortest surface-path between them. In this sense, the minor arc is analogous to “straight lines” in Euclidean geometry. The length of the minor arc of a <b>great</b> <b>circle</b> is taken as the distance between two points on a surface of a sphere in Riemannian geometry where such <b>great</b> <b>circles</b> are called Riemannian <b>circles.</b> These <b>great</b> <b>circles</b> are the geodesics of the sphere.|$|R
